{% comment %}
  gazelle-layout — THE single source of truth for global page width.
  Added 14 July 2026.

  Why: Horizon's page_width theme setting is "narrow", which the theme resolves to
  --narrow-page-width: 90rem (~1400px). Every June mockup and every gazelle- custom
  section is built to 1200px. Rather than a per-page hack (this replaces the local
  --page-width override that used to live in gazelle-cover-styles.liquid), we set the
  global page width here, once.

  How: we override --page-content-width only, and let Horizon's native calc derive
  --page-width from it. base.css declares both on the body via .page-width-narrow:

    --page-content-width: var(--narrow-page-width);
    --page-width: calc(var(--page-content-width) + (var(--page-margin) * 2));

  var() inside a custom property resolves at computed-value time against that property's
  computed value ON THE SAME ELEMENT. So the cascade settles --page-content-width to our
  1200px first (body.page-width-narrow, 0-1-1, beats base.css's .page-width-narrow, 0-1-0),
  and the native --page-width calc then derives calc(1200px + var(--page-margin) * 2) from
  it — the same result as the explicit override this replaces, but with BOTH variables now
  agreeing at 1200. That agreement is the point: --page-content-width also feeds
  --util-page-margin-offset (base.css .section), which carousel / edge-offset components
  read. Leaving it at the 90rem preset while --page-width said 1200 is what caused the
  featured-collection bleed found in the 14 Jul sweep.

  Note: --page-width is declared on <body>, NOT :root, so a :root override would be shadowed
  by the body's own declaration — hence the body selector. It is body.page-width-narrow ONLY,
  deliberately: scoped to the current "narrow" setting so the theme-editor page-width control
  stays a live escape hatch — switch the setting to any other preset and this override stops
  applying, restoring native behaviour.

  Known gap: sections/main-blog.liquid re-declares both variables on .blog-posts, so the blog
  page keeps the native preset width regardless of this snippet. It is a Horizon core file, so
  it is left alone.

  Emits a {% style %} block only — no markup. Rendered from layout/theme.liquid, adjacent to
  the gazelle-fonts hook (last in <head>).
{% endcomment %}

{% style %}
  body.page-width-narrow {
    --page-content-width: 1200px;
  }

  /* Featured-collection carousel width fix.
     product-list's carousel layout hard-codes the `force-full-width` class on its
     wrapper (snippets/resource-list.liquid), so base.css's
     `.section > .force-full-width { grid-column: 1 / -1 }` breaks the scroll track
     out to full viewport width even when section_width is "page-width". This is
     native Horizon behaviour, applied unconditionally for layout_type: carousel —
     there is NO native setting to disable it (confirmed in the theme editor,
     16 July 2026: page-width set, carousel still breaks out).

     Fix: re-place the wrapper in the constrained centre column (grid-column: 2) so
     the track respects the 1200px content box, and zero --util-page-margin-offset
     on this subtree — it feeds the full-bleed first-slide inset (--gutter-slide-width)
     and the arrow padding, both sized for a viewport-width track. The peek affordance
     is untouched: it is reserved inside the slide-width calc via --peek-next-slide-size,
     independent of container width.

     Specificity 0,3,0 (.section-resource-list + .resource-list__carousel + .force-full-width)
     beats core's 0,2,0 (.section > .force-full-width), so no !important is needed. */
  .section-resource-list > .resource-list__carousel.force-full-width {
    grid-column: 2;
    --util-page-margin-offset: 0px;
  }
{% endstyle %}
